pullRequest.body:
This PR introduces a version of the Hadamard three-lines theorem (see [here](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hadamard_three-lines_theorem)), which is a prerequisite for norm interpolation. This project was suggested by @dupuisf earlier this year. This is my first decently sized PR so thank you for your patience if I have made any mistakes!

---

Sorry about this, I got a bit stuck on the other suggestions and forgot to push the changes I had made.

Hey everyone!

I would like to revive this PR. There have been two notable changes:
1. The main proof is now based on Phragmén-Lindelöf. The old proof used basically the same ideas.
2. After a comment of @sgouezel, I noticed that my proof did not cover the edge case of either of the borders being 0. I have added this, the proof uses a limit argument. If someone know a quicker way to do this with the same hypotheses, please do share! I could only find a quicker proof that required `[Mul E]`.

Finally, I would like to apologize for taking so much time.
Best,
Xavier

```suggestion
lemma inv_interp_strip_diff_cont (f : ℂ → ℂ) : DiffContOnCl ℂ (invInterpStrip f) (strip 0 1) := by
  by_cases (sSupAbsIm f 0) = 0 ∨ (sSupAbsIm f 1) = 0
  case pos =>
    -- Case everywhere 0
    -- Starting with Lemma to handle rewriting of invInterpStrip as a function.
    have hzero : invInterpStrip f = 0 := by
      rw [funext_iff]
      intro z
      simp only [inv_interp_strip_of_zero_def z f h, Pi.zero_apply, eq_self_iff_true]
    rw [hzero, Pi.zero_def]
    exact diffContOnCl_const

  case neg =>
    -- Case nowhere 0
    push_neg at h
    cases' h with h0 h1
    rw [ne_comm] at h0 h1
    apply Differentiable.diffContOnCl
    intro z
    -- Same strategy.
    have hpos: invInterpStrip f = fun (z : ℂ) ↦ (sSupAbsIm f 0)^(z-1) * (sSupAbsIm f 1)^(-z) := by
      funext z
      rw [inv_interp_strip_of_pos_def z f (lt_of_le_of_ne (sSupAbsIm_nonneg f 0) h0)
      (lt_of_le_of_ne (sSupAbsIm_nonneg f 1) h1)]
    rw [hpos]
    apply DifferentiableAt.mul _ _
    · apply DifferentiableAt.const_cpow (DifferentiableAt.sub_const (differentiableAt_id') 1) _
      left; simp only [Ne.def, ofReal_eq_zero]; rwa [eq_comm]
    · apply DifferentiableAt.const_cpow _ _
      rw [differentiableAt_neg_iff]
      apply differentiableAt_id'
      left; simp only [Ne.def, ofReal_eq_zero]; rwa [eq_comm]
```
Since the `by_cases` generates two goals, we need to separate them visually in the code, either like this or using bullet points. The same goes for the `apply` in the second bullet point below. Also, it's better to use `refine` with `?_` for the holes that are expected to become new goals; I think most people expect `apply` to only generate one goal, and the `_` to be filled in automatically. (Also, with `refine`, you can actually name your new goals with the syntax `?mynewgoal`, and then you can use `case mynewgoal =>` afterwards.)
